WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.600
So these are my disclosures. You know, what I thought would be an interesting thing for this group, because like we heard, this is a AML very much based therapy, but it's something that isn't very common in sort of the matrix of how this trial worked is not very common.

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:32.840
So I thought it'd be a nice introduction to say, how are we doing things in AML in a more broad sense? And then it's nice that we'll look at some of the very fine granular aspects that are coming up in the future. And what's really good right now is that my timer hasn't started, so I can at least just keep going.

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:42.540
So what I'm going to talk about, what I'm going to talk about Myelomatch. So Myelomatch is this NCI sponsored initiative that's for both AML and MDS.

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:48.540
And many of you may have heard and seen some studies with what's called the BEAT AML trial, which is another broad trial.

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:55.860
That's sort of a nationwide trial. This is a little bit different in the sense that it's a bit broader, it covers a bit larger population.

00:00:55.860 --> 00:01:06.760
And the thought is that if you can create a master screening protocol, and I'm going to just sort of plow through some of these for a moment, if you can create a master protocol where we can get everybody screened.

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:17.660
And not only get everybody screened with having a DNA and cytogenetics and mutational status, but then have a number of different trials underneath that, that patients would be eligible for.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:17.660
You'd really not only get a DNA and cytogenetics and mutational status, but then have a number of different trials underneath that, that patients would be eligible for.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:17.660
You'd really not only get a DNA and cytogenetics and mutational status, but then have a number of different trials underneath that, that patients would be eligible for.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:33.840
You'd really not only capture the entire AML population, but you'd also have numerous novel agents that fit certain mutational properties, because the bottom line is, as you've heard from most of the people here, it's really about coming through with targeted mutations now in AML.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:42.460
We're breaking AML down from one disease where everyone just got the same chemotherapy to numerous separate diseases based on individual mutations.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:47.520
And the concept is what we do is we get these protocol, we get these mutations.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:47.860
And the concept is what we do is we get these protocol, we get these mutations.

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:55.400
And the key is all the molecular studies are done ideally within 72 hours, which isn't something that happens in the real world.

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:58.440
There's a lot of centers that it takes two weeks to get the molecular studies back.

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:00.520
So the key is the rapidity of getting this done.

00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:06.200
And then they get this initial treatment that's a targeted treatment based upon their own mutational status.

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:08.460
It's kind of a personalized medicine type concept.

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:17.560
What then happens and what we're at now is we can then stratify after that to what's called Tier 2, which is called MRD, which you can see on the second line.

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:21.460
And that's how do we eradicate any disease and what's the best way to eradicate that.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:26.140
So that has a series of trials that the patient can pass through depending on their MRD status.

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:30.660
And then there's a transplant trial after that to say, OK, now we've got them in MRD.

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:32.100
How do we get them to transplant?

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:35.020
And what's the best way to transplant?

00:02:35.140 --> 00:02:39.900
There's some trials that actually are employing venetoclax that are going to be opened up in the transplant setting.

00:02:40.280 --> 00:02:47.040
So that's sort of the basic pattern to say, how do we take such a diverse, broad group and make this available?

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:51.540
To them with rapid responses in terms of molecular studies.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:58.060
So we looked at the first 500 patients and what we saw was that of the first 500 patients, some screen failed.

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:01.700
The screen failed may mean that they're just too sick to even wait for their studies to come back.

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.440
They just have to go on some type of dealer's choice treatment.

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:12.460
Now, what I didn't mention in the previous study is that in that dealer's choice treatment, if you don't, if this site doesn't have a particular study open,

00:03:12.460 --> 00:03:17.620
they go on what's called the Tier Advancement Protocol, meaning that the site can put in what they feel is a standard.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:26.740
And then they can go on to a different trial at a later state if they have that trial open, whether it's the MRD trial or the transplant trial.

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:32.920
But anyway, 76 patients, so about a sixth of the patients or so didn't have AML.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:35.760
They had ALL, they had aplastic anemia, they had something else.

00:03:35.780 --> 00:03:36.860
So they were tossed as well.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:43.420
And we found that about 90% of these patients had AML and a good portion of these patients, about 10% had MDS.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:46.860
Very heavily towards the white population.

00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:57.340
And age range was about 63, which is very important because these trials have the cutoff of age 60, where we think of younger adult trials as age 60, older adult trials as over the age of 60.

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:04.880
I'm heading now the young adult trial, and I find it somewhat depressing that when we started this trial, I would have been in the younger category.

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:09.420
I think when we end the trial and publish something, I won't qualify for any of the trials that I'll be overseeing.

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:17.260
But this is really the take-home study, which is, can we take these studies and can we get results within 72 hours?

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:35.880
And what we found was, barring a few different screen fails or a few issues with individual samples, 95% of people were able to get the results within 72 hours, which is really an incredible breakthrough, because when we look at the BEAT AML study, which is sort of the other predecessor towards this, that goal was to get everything back within a week.

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:40.260
So 72 hours is really important to try to get the results quickly.

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:47.060
And then what we've also seen is, as this has moved forward, and it's been a slow process because the screening process is really slow.

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:55.100
And so there's a significant lag time.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:05:03.220
But as you can see, it really started off with a very slow enrollment, but you can see the enrollment to each individual randomized trial has been increasing over time.

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:16.840
Now, what's really nice about this is we can look at a large volume of molecular data, and we can actually see what the molecular construct is for the general patient population, which will help us look towards the future to say, what can we use for this?

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:17.820
What can we use for different trials?

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:19.320
Where are our best opportunities?

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:24.680
So we can see in the AML group, 25% of these people have NPM1 mutations.

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:28.920
So this is really going to be very fertile ground to look at all of these men inhibitors that we have.

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:31.460
We see FLT3 in about 15%.

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:33.380
It somewhat mirrors the population.

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:43.660
But what's really interesting, and we were talking about this earlier just at breakfast, is when you look at the MDS population, almost 40% of patients have a TP53.

00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:46.660
So this is obviously an incredibly fertile ground for us to say, what can we do?

00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:48.660
What can we look at in terms of clinical trials?

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:51.540
Because these MDS trials are going to enroll very quickly.

00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:58.760
For those of you who don't do AML, TP53 is sort of the holy grail of mutations.

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:03.320
It's the one that Tomas has been working on for a while, and we just haven't been able to find something that works.

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:07.500
It's kind of like, I think of it as like the Darth Vader or the New York Yankees of AML mutations.

00:06:09.180 --> 00:06:11.460
You know, where are we in terms of what people are doing?

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:15.540
And I think this is interesting based on some of the data that Sasha talked about with the PARADIGM trial.

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:16.540
We looked and said,

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:19.860
all right, the people that are getting treated off protocol, what are they receiving?

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:27.440
And we find that 62% of people are getting intensive chemotherapy still, 38% are getting HMA-VEN.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.720
And what's interesting is this is all before PARADIGM.

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:32.080
And I think there's going to be some significant changes.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:40.280
What I was kind of shocked with is that in the patients that were age 60 to 75, almost half of them were still getting intensive chemotherapy.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:46.060
And I think that's going to remarkably change based on the data that Sasha put forward with the PARADIGM trial.

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:49.240
You know, there are currently five open trials.

00:06:49.340 --> 00:06:50.640
There are about two more trials.

00:06:50.780 --> 00:06:58.180
There's the young adult, the young adult good risk trial, which Sella Houston is in charge of.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:01.740
And that's going to be open next week, hopefully next week, maybe two weeks.

00:07:02.140 --> 00:07:06.900
There's another IDH trial that we're expecting to open in the next couple of weeks.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:09.000
But these are the five trials that are open.

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:10.720
And so it's nice to see these enrolling.

00:07:11.020 --> 00:07:14.240
And they're enrolling now at a pretty good clip now that more centers have these open.

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:16.260
And so conclusion, you know,

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:22.020
Myelomatch, as of two weeks ago, we just broke the 1,000th patient that's been screened for that protocol.

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:27.900
So that's really important to just see how this has ramped up over the past really six months or so.

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:32.260
We've been able to meet the turnaround goal of turnaround time goal of about 72 hours.

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:34.340
And we currently have five trials open.

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:39.940
But in the end, we're looking at about 17, 18 trials and sort of a mix and match.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:46.100
So when we look at, for example, the FLIT3 trial, the FLIT3 trial in the elderly, which is randomizing to,

00:07:46.180 --> 00:07:54.300
we'll be able to pick the winner of that and then move another drug into that trial as well.

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:57.360
So this is going to have subsequent trials moving forward.

00:07:57.860 --> 00:07:59.300
So I thank you all for your time.

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:04.600
This has been a Herculean effort by a lot of people involved in this entire study.

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:05.540
But appreciate it.
